1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:29,980
 Ovo je podcast Mrežnica. Dobrodošli. Naš današnji gost je gospodin Michael Palaić, amerikanac hrvatskih korjena i čovjeka o čijem bi se želi.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:53,000
 u životu definitivno mogao i trebao snimiti film. A zašto to govorim? Iz jednostavnog razloga što je gospodin Palaić prije još 1990. godine snimio film Blajburška tragedija, točnije dokumentarac, o jednom od najvećih zločina nad hrvatskim narodom počinjenom u svibnju 1945. godine.

3
00:00:53,000 --> 00:01:04,000
 No tu priči nije kraj. Tijekom domovinskog rata gospodin Palaić bio je u Hrvatskoj kao novinar. Bio je kao novinar i u Bosni i Hercegovini tijekom tamošnjih sukoba.

4
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:25,860
 Napisao je knjigu za Hrvatsku moje bake. Ali, ponovno ću reći, i tu nije kraj njegovom doista bogatom životnom putu. Završio je na FBI-ovoj listi, a Sjedinjene američke države protiv njega su podigle optužnicu za kriumčarenje oružja. Prijatila mu je kazna zatvora od 60 godina.

5
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:38,540
 Danas je gospodin Palaić naš gost. Reći ću da smo ga uhvatili na odmoru u Hrvatskoj u koju radu dolazi zajedno sa suprugom Sandrom i da mi je velika čast što je danas ovdje.

6
00:01:38,540 --> 00:01:46,740
 Pa za početak najprije reći ću na hrvatskom gospodine Palaiću dobrodošli u naš podcast. Velika mi je čast što ste danas ovdje.

7
00:01:46,980 --> 00:01:48,900
 Hvala vam, hvala na pozivu.

8
00:01:48,900 --> 00:01:55,680
 Izvrsno, evo. Pa zapravo mogli bismo možda i nastaviti na hrvatskom, no šalim se.

9
00:01:55,680 --> 00:02:04,460
 Dogovorili smo, razumijete hrvatski, snalazite se s hrvatskim jezikom, no ipak ćemo na engleskom da vama bude ugodnije.

10
00:02:04,460 --> 00:02:05,380
 Može tako?

11
00:02:05,380 --> 00:02:05,940
 Može.

12
00:02:05,940 --> 00:02:15,240
 Zvukajte se svoje kvijali. Kod je vrša u USA i kod je?

13
00:02:15,240 --> 00:02:31,080
 Moje vrša i vrša zvukom petrinja. Vrša zvukom sezvanili sezvanili sezvanili sezvanili sezvanili sezvanili. Vrša zvukom 1910. Vrša zvukom 1912.

14
00:02:32,520 --> 00:02:34,520
 So, they came to Detroit, Michigan,

15
00:02:34,520 --> 00:02:36,520
 which was, at the time, a major...

16
00:02:36,520 --> 00:02:37,520
 It still is a major city,

17
00:02:37,520 --> 00:02:40,520
 but it was really a thriving major city at the time.

18
00:02:40,520 --> 00:02:41,520
 So, that's why they came there.

19
00:02:41,520 --> 00:02:43,520
 There was a lot of employment.

20
00:02:43,520 --> 00:02:45,520
 The economy was fantastic.

21
00:02:45,520 --> 00:02:47,520
 So, they came there from Petrina.

22
00:02:47,520 --> 00:02:50,520
 And, with the exception of my grandfather,

23
00:02:50,520 --> 00:02:52,520
 who only went back once,

24
00:02:52,520 --> 00:02:54,520
 they never returned again,

25
00:02:54,520 --> 00:02:57,520
 especially because World War I started,

26
00:02:57,520 --> 00:02:59,520
 and then, of course, World War II,

27
00:02:59,520 --> 00:03:01,520
 and they couldn't return.

28
00:03:01,520 --> 00:03:04,520
 And they had no sympathy for the Yugoslav government,

29
00:03:04,520 --> 00:03:07,520
 so they didn't want to come back.

30
00:03:07,520 --> 00:03:11,520
 And they died before they were able to see independent Croatia.

31
00:03:11,520 --> 00:03:14,520
 Have you always felt your Croatian roots?

32
00:03:14,520 --> 00:03:18,520
 And who is responsible for that?

33
00:03:18,520 --> 00:03:22,520
 In our family, we always grew up knowing we were Croatian.

34
00:03:22,520 --> 00:03:24,520
 We never used the word...

35
00:03:24,520 --> 00:03:25,520
 We never used the term Yugoslavia,

36
00:03:25,520 --> 00:03:27,520
 referring to our nationality.

37
00:03:27,520 --> 00:03:30,520
 It was always Croatian.

38
00:03:30,520 --> 00:03:33,520
 Probably mainly because there was no Yugoslavia

39
00:03:33,520 --> 00:03:36,520
 when my grandfather and my grandmother came to America.

40
00:03:36,520 --> 00:03:38,520
 It was Austria-Hungarian Empire at the time.

41
00:03:38,520 --> 00:03:41,520
 So, there was no...

42
00:03:41,520 --> 00:03:44,520
 They felt nothing for Yugoslavia.

43
00:03:44,520 --> 00:03:50,520
 And they only referred to each other and to us as Croatians.

44
00:03:50,520 --> 00:03:51,520
 Mm-hmm.

45
00:03:51,520 --> 00:03:52,520
 Tell me.

46
00:03:52,520 --> 00:03:54,520
 Tell me more, if you want.

47
00:03:54,520 --> 00:03:55,520
 So...

48
00:03:55,520 --> 00:04:00,520
 Who is responsible for your feelings towards your Croatian roots?

49
00:04:00,520 --> 00:04:03,520
 You know, I thought about that over the years,

50
00:04:03,520 --> 00:04:05,520
 and I included it in my book,

51
00:04:05,520 --> 00:04:07,520
 "Zahravatsko Moje Baka".

52
00:04:07,520 --> 00:04:18,520
 I think the roots were with my grandmother because I spent the first five years of my life with my grandmother.

53
00:04:18,520 --> 00:04:19,520
 She took care of me.

54
00:04:19,520 --> 00:04:20,520
 My mother was working.

55
00:04:20,520 --> 00:04:21,520
 My father was working.

56
00:04:21,520 --> 00:04:28,520
 And I was with her 100% of the time, you know, until they got off work and picked me up.

57
00:04:28,520 --> 00:04:31,520
 I spent the whole day with Baka.

58
00:04:31,520 --> 00:04:40,520
 And I guess I got to love the Croatian culture because I loved her so much.

59
00:04:40,520 --> 00:04:42,520
 She was a fantastic grandma.

60
00:04:42,520 --> 00:04:43,520
 What was her name?

61
00:04:43,520 --> 00:04:45,520
 Her name was Lubica.

62
00:04:45,520 --> 00:04:46,520
 Lubica.

63
00:04:46,520 --> 00:04:47,520
 Lubica.

64
00:04:47,520 --> 00:04:55,520
 So, you know, just the daily things of watching her, how much love she had.

65
00:04:55,520 --> 00:04:59,520
 If she was cutting a pear, she would give me a piece of the pear.

66
00:04:59,520 --> 00:05:03,520
 If I would watch her making strudel on the kitchen table.

67
00:05:03,520 --> 00:05:06,520
 And I just, I was in love with the woman, you know,

68
00:05:06,520 --> 00:05:10,520
 because she was just a fantastic woman to grow up around.

69
00:05:10,520 --> 00:05:12,520
 And she was so full of love and she gave me love.

70
00:05:12,520 --> 00:05:17,520
 And I think that was where the roots came from originally, I believe.

71
00:05:17,520 --> 00:05:18,520
 Yeah.

72
00:05:18,520 --> 00:05:22,520
 We will return to your Croatian story a little bit later.

73
00:05:22,520 --> 00:05:27,520
 Let's shift focus to your documentary, Blajburska tragedija.

74
00:05:27,520 --> 00:05:32,520
 You made a documentary film about this tragedy.

75
00:05:32,520 --> 00:05:33,520
 Why?

76
00:05:33,520 --> 00:05:41,520
 I was originally introduced to the whole story of Blajburg just through discussions with people.

77
00:05:41,520 --> 00:05:51,520
 So, you know, in America, in Australia, Argentina, Europe, we tend to live in kind of, especially in the days that I grew up in,

78
00:05:51,520 --> 00:05:56,520
 we grew up in kind of subcultures of America.

79
00:05:56,520 --> 00:05:59,520
 So, I went to a Croatian Catholic church.

80
00:05:59,520 --> 00:06:02,520
 We went to Croatian picnics.

81
00:06:02,520 --> 00:06:03,520
 My friends were Croatian.

82
00:06:03,520 --> 00:06:05,520
 I associated with Croatians.

83
00:06:05,520 --> 00:06:09,520
 And so, you hear what, about Blajburg.

84
00:06:09,520 --> 00:06:14,520
 And this was back, you know, when I was in my early twenties, I would hear these stories.

85
00:06:14,520 --> 00:06:25,520
 And growing up in America, I, of course, America is more of an Anglo-Saxon culture in general, with subcultures inside of it.

86
00:06:25,520 --> 00:06:40,520
 And I couldn't really believe that the British are capable of being so uncaring, so violating human rights like they did in Blajburg.

87
00:06:40,520 --> 00:06:44,520
 Being treacherous in their deception towards Croatians.

88
00:06:44,520 --> 00:06:49,520
 And I grew up with this idea that it can't be possible.

89
00:06:49,520 --> 00:06:52,520
 So, I had to really do my research on my own.

90
00:06:52,520 --> 00:06:54,520
 I read "Operation Slaughterhouse."

91
00:06:54,520 --> 00:07:04,520
 That was the first book I read about Blajburg by Priscilla, and I forgot the other author's name.

92
00:07:04,520 --> 00:07:08,520
 And it just kind of shook me.

93
00:07:08,520 --> 00:07:14,520
 But I could also see that there were some survivors of Blajburg that I know about.

94
00:07:14,520 --> 00:07:17,520
 And they were becoming fewer and fewer of them.

95
00:07:17,520 --> 00:07:19,520
 And they were getting older and older.

96
00:07:19,520 --> 00:07:26,520
 And I thought, why can't we do something similar to what the Jewish people did with the Jewish Holocaust.

97
00:07:26,520 --> 00:07:33,520
 And document the stories of these people, these individuals that witnessed Blajburg.

98
00:07:33,520 --> 00:07:37,520
 And get it on film, get it on, you know, videotape.

99
00:07:37,520 --> 00:07:43,520
 And document it so that it is there for as long as the film exists.

100
00:07:43,520 --> 00:07:49,520
 And thank God I did that, because so many people that I interviewed back then survived.

101
00:07:49,520 --> 00:07:50,520
 I mean, didn't survive.

102
00:07:50,520 --> 00:07:52,520
 They died shortly afterwards.

103
00:07:52,520 --> 00:08:02,520
 So, that was my basic idea, just to get these individuals on videotape.

104
00:08:02,520 --> 00:08:16,520
 As we got closer to the war in '91, I'm talking about probably 1989, '88, I could see that Croatia was moving towards independence.

105
00:08:16,520 --> 00:08:21,520
 It was, for me, it was a foregone conclusion that it was going to happen.

106
00:08:21,520 --> 00:08:23,520
 That it was going to ask for independence.

107
00:08:23,520 --> 00:08:27,520
 That it was going to have to fight for independence if they wanted it.

108
00:08:27,520 --> 00:08:45,520
 And I saw the relationship between what happened in 1945 with losing independence and freedom and military, with what would happen if Croatia, once they declared independence in 1991, what would happen?

109
00:08:45,520 --> 00:08:56,520
 And I was, I believed 100% that the same thing would happen in 19, whenever the end of the war came, 1995, or whenever the end of the war came.

110
00:08:56,520 --> 00:09:08,520
 If Croatia had given up and lost the fight, there would have been mass slaughter just like there was after World War II.

111
00:09:08,520 --> 00:09:29,520
 So, I wanted to use the film as a vehicle to tell people, especially political leadership like Tujman and, at the time, Pataga was a leadership, Gotovac and, you know, various people, Shushak, how important it was to win the war.

112
00:09:29,520 --> 00:09:36,520
 If you're going to start it, you can't lose and you can't give up because you'll be butchered either way.

113
00:09:36,520 --> 00:09:38,520
 So, it was very important.

114
00:09:38,520 --> 00:09:48,520
 And so, I thought that the film was a good motivation for people to understand, at least from my point of view, what was going to happen if they didn't win the war.

115
00:09:48,520 --> 00:09:57,520
 You spoke to those who survived or the massacre or who managed to escape. What did they tell you?

116
00:09:57,520 --> 00:10:12,520
 Well, each of the individuals have their own story. So, but one thing that was common is that they all witnessed massacre.

117
00:10:12,520 --> 00:10:25,520
 They witnessed like bloodthirsty massacre and sometimes you can't explain how these partisans would treat the Croatian soldiers.

118
00:10:25,520 --> 00:10:45,520
 And the closer, the closer they got into, or farther away from the border with Austria, the more bloodthirsty the partisans would get, including women who were very bloodthirsty in the way they attacked people with knives, for example.

119
00:10:45,520 --> 00:10:48,520
 And they took pleasure from it. That was the strange thing.

120
00:10:48,520 --> 00:10:50,520
 Pure evil.

121
00:10:50,520 --> 00:11:01,520
 I don't know how else you could describe it. The hatred and the pure evil that they had and the way they were killing people, the way they enjoyed it.

122
00:11:01,520 --> 00:11:12,520
 And we can talk later, but I experienced the same thing when I interviewed people during the war from the War of Independence with Croatia, which I call it.

123
00:11:12,520 --> 00:11:18,520
 I don't call it the Homeland War. I call it the War of Independence between '91 and '95.

124
00:11:18,520 --> 00:11:25,520
 And so very, very similar stories then. But yeah, that's one thing they did have in common.

125
00:11:25,520 --> 00:11:32,520
 And just how they were treated as they were, and they had no hope of surviving, they didn't think.

126
00:11:32,520 --> 00:11:37,520
 Many of them would give people messages, you know, I can't make it anymore.

127
00:11:37,520 --> 00:11:47,520
 If I don't make it, tell my parents I love them, give my greetings to my family. If I make it, I don't make it and you do.

128
00:11:47,520 --> 00:11:49,520
 So those kind of things.

129
00:11:49,520 --> 00:11:54,520
 What did they tell you about escaping and surrendering?

130
00:11:54,520 --> 00:12:07,520
 I would often ask people how long the column was that was escaping.

131
00:12:07,520 --> 00:12:13,520
 I don't even like to use the word escaping because Croatian, from all of the people that I talked to,

132
00:12:13,520 --> 00:12:20,520
 the Croatians did not lose any battles, major battles with the partisans during World War II.

133
00:12:20,520 --> 00:12:23,520
 They weren't escaping the partisans.

134
00:12:23,520 --> 00:12:31,520
 They were going towards the British in hopes of surrendering so that they didn't have to fight the British in addition to the partisans.

135
00:12:31,520 --> 00:12:37,520
 They could have easily fought the partisans according to all the people that I interviewed.

136
00:12:37,520 --> 00:12:44,520
 But it wasn't that they were running from the partisans, they were running towards Blybird to surrender to the British.

137
00:12:44,520 --> 00:12:48,520
 So I'm sorry, I forgot what the original was.

138
00:12:48,520 --> 00:12:54,520
 What did they tell you about escaping and surrendering? Can you share this story with us, please?

139
00:12:54,520 --> 00:13:02,520
 When I asked them how long the column was, they couldn't see the beginning and they couldn't see the end.

140
00:13:02,520 --> 00:13:15,520
 One person, in fact, I have him on the YouTube channel, talks about he got into Blybird in the late evening.

141
00:13:15,520 --> 00:13:17,520
 It was still not dark.

142
00:13:17,520 --> 00:13:21,520
 And they were camping on the mountain outside of Blybird field.

143
00:13:21,520 --> 00:13:27,520
 And then in the middle of the night, he woke up and he saw what looked like a city below him.

144
00:13:27,520 --> 00:13:33,520
 And he said to his friend, "How is it that I didn't see this city when we came here?"

145
00:13:33,520 --> 00:13:37,520
 And the person told him, "That's not a city. Those are our people down there.

146
00:13:37,520 --> 00:13:41,520
 And they have lights lit, torches lit, candles lit.

147
00:13:41,520 --> 00:13:43,520
 And it's not a city, it's the people."

148
00:13:43,520 --> 00:13:49,520
 It was just such a huge mass of human beings down there.

149
00:13:49,520 --> 00:13:55,520
 So, the only thing that they could see, because they weren't involved in the negotiations,

150
00:13:55,520 --> 00:14:05,520
 was at a certain time, 3 or 4 o'clock in the afternoon, on May 15, 1945, white flags went up.

151
00:14:05,520 --> 00:14:14,520
 Meaning that they were, that their leadership had made us an agreement to surrender.

152
00:14:14,520 --> 00:14:26,520
 Now, we can talk about who they surrendered to, but for one thing, one thing is for sure that the British refused the surrender.

153
00:14:26,520 --> 00:14:34,520
 Knowing that they were going to be killed when they went back into, were taken back into Yugoslavia by the partisans.

154
00:14:34,520 --> 00:14:38,520
 The British knew that. I think the documents point that out.

155
00:14:38,520 --> 00:14:42,520
 So, who were the murderers? Only partisans, or?

156
00:14:42,520 --> 00:14:44,520
 Good question.

157
00:14:44,520 --> 00:15:00,520
 I would judge the situation like the Allied Army judged the losers of the World War II, for example. Nuremberg.

158
00:15:00,520 --> 00:15:06,520
 I interviewed a Nuremberg prosecutor who was also on my YouTube channel.

159
00:15:06,520 --> 00:15:12,520
 The Nuremberg prosecutor, according to his definition of war crimes,

160
00:15:12,520 --> 00:15:20,520
 was that the British were responsible for war crimes because they knew that these people were going to be killed.

161
00:15:20,520 --> 00:15:31,520
 And if they didn't know, they should have known. So, they were in violation already of what already existed at the time, the Geneva Convention of 1928,

162
00:15:31,520 --> 00:15:38,520
 which protected prisoners and the civilians that were following the surrendered soldiers.

163
00:15:38,520 --> 00:15:47,520
 So, they were in violation of that. Now, this is according to the Nuremberg prosecutor, who is also British, who is saying this.

164
00:15:47,520 --> 00:15:48,520
 What was his name?

165
00:15:48,520 --> 00:15:49,520
 Gerald Draper.

166
00:15:49,520 --> 00:15:50,520
 Mm-hmm.

167
00:15:50,520 --> 00:16:00,520
 And he's famous. His specialty was war crimes. He had started off as a Nuremberg prosecutor,

168
00:16:00,520 --> 00:16:06,520
 frequently went to Israel as an honored guest because of his involvement with war crimes.

169
00:16:06,520 --> 00:16:11,520
 He wrote many of the laws subsequent to World War II about war crimes.

170
00:16:11,520 --> 00:16:18,520
 So, I don't know what better expert that you could have talk about the crimes that were committed by the British,

171
00:16:18,520 --> 00:16:24,520
 but a former British major with the British Nuremberg trials.

172
00:16:24,520 --> 00:16:28,520
 How did you manage to get them to share their story with you?

173
00:16:28,520 --> 00:16:36,520
 Well, I was already doing the interviews with various Croatian eyewitnesses, survivors,

174
00:16:36,520 --> 00:16:47,520
 and I went to Toronto, Canada because Nikolai Tolstoy was going to be there speaking at one event with the Croatian people.

175
00:16:47,520 --> 00:16:55,520
 And it was a very small event. There was only probably 20 people in this room at the Civic Center in Toronto, Ontario.

176
00:16:55,520 --> 00:17:03,520
 But I knew he was going to be there because my friend, who had been a friend for quite a while, even at that time, Ante Belio,

177
00:17:03,520 --> 00:17:10,520
 who later ended up in Croatia doing some great things for the Tudjmi government.

178
00:17:10,520 --> 00:17:20,520
 He told me and we went there and after the talk was over, I went out for lunch with Tolstoy and Belio,

179
00:17:20,520 --> 00:17:29,520
 and I went there and I was talking and eventually I approached Tolstoy with the idea that I would like to interview these people.

180
00:17:29,520 --> 00:17:36,520
 Can you make the contact with me? Give me the contacts and I will write to them and hopefully there'll be some positive response.

181
00:17:36,520 --> 00:17:46,520
 Interesting thing is, when I first wrote to these people, they claimed that they didn't know too much about Blyberg.

182
00:17:46,520 --> 00:17:47,520
 How's that?

183
00:17:47,520 --> 00:17:48,520
 Exactly.

184
00:17:48,520 --> 00:17:53,520
 That they weren't there, that they were dealing mostly with Cossacks,

185
00:17:53,520 --> 00:17:58,520
 that they didn't have too much involvement directly with Blyberg and with the Croatians.

186
00:17:58,520 --> 00:18:01,520
 It turned out that's exactly false.

187
00:18:01,520 --> 00:18:14,520
 And I think that because I was American, with the American accent, I wasn't coming from a position that they thought was pro-Croatian, let's say.

188
00:18:14,520 --> 00:18:21,520
 That they thought I would be more neutral and it's a little difficult to be neutral when your people have been butchered.

189
00:18:21,520 --> 00:18:22,520
 Of course.

190
00:18:22,520 --> 00:18:23,520
 So…

191
00:18:23,520 --> 00:18:24,520
 Please go on.

192
00:18:24,520 --> 00:18:32,520
 So, I finally did get permission from these people and they gave me directions to their home and I went to visit each one of them

193
00:18:32,520 --> 00:18:38,520
 and I discovered that actually they knew much more about Blyberg and the repatriations of Croatians and others.

194
00:18:38,520 --> 00:18:40,520
 There were Serbs and Slovenians also repatriated.

195
00:18:40,520 --> 00:18:47,520
 Yes, I wanted to ask you, besides the Croats, who are the other people there in Blyberg?

196
00:18:47,520 --> 00:18:53,520
 In Blyberg itself, mostly like 99% were Croatians.

197
00:18:53,520 --> 00:18:56,520
 There were some Germans that were in the group too.

198
00:18:56,520 --> 00:19:02,520
 But most of the ones in Blyberg were all Croatian people from either Croatian civilians.

199
00:19:02,520 --> 00:19:08,520
 Again, 500,000 Croatian civilians according to the British documents.

200
00:19:08,520 --> 00:19:14,520
 The British documents that I found in the archives in London and 200,000 soldiers.

201
00:19:14,520 --> 00:19:15,520
 So, altogether 700…

202
00:19:15,520 --> 00:19:17,520
 Disarmed soldiers.

203
00:19:17,520 --> 00:19:18,520
 Disarmed soldiers.

204
00:19:18,520 --> 00:19:21,520
 They were eventually disarmed soldiers.

205
00:19:21,520 --> 00:19:22,520
 That's right.

206
00:19:22,520 --> 00:19:25,520
 What was the most interesting thing that you found?

207
00:19:25,520 --> 00:19:27,520
 The most interesting thing about Blyberg?

208
00:19:27,520 --> 00:19:28,520
 Yes.

209
00:19:28,520 --> 00:19:32,520
 And about the British role in the story.

210
00:19:32,520 --> 00:19:33,520
 Well, yeah.

211
00:19:33,520 --> 00:19:35,520
 Well, that's a good question.

212
00:19:35,520 --> 00:19:36,520
 Thank you.

213
00:19:36,520 --> 00:19:42,520
 Blyberg in itself is a very terrible story.

214
00:19:42,520 --> 00:19:44,520
 The story of deception.

215
00:19:44,520 --> 00:19:53,520
 The story of refusing protection to 500,000 women and children that asked for protection of the British government.

216
00:19:53,520 --> 00:20:04,520
 200,000 Croatian soldiers who had surrendered their arms to the British, thinking that they were going to get protection from the British.

217
00:20:04,520 --> 00:20:08,520
 That was bad enough.

218
00:20:08,520 --> 00:20:24,520
 And then you learn there's an additional situation where an officer, an intelligence officer named Nicolai, Captain Nicholson, Nigel Nicholson was involved with it.

219
00:20:24,520 --> 00:20:34,520
 And that was a very well-constructed method of deception telling these Croatian soldiers that…

220
00:20:34,520 --> 00:20:46,520
 There were some Croatian soldiers that made it into the area after Blyberg between May 17, let's say in June, the end of June.

221
00:20:46,520 --> 00:20:58,520
 There was Croatian soldiers that had filtered up that weren't part of the original column in Blyberg.

222
00:20:58,520 --> 00:21:04,520
 And there's estimated about 25,000 to 30,000 of these Croatian soldiers.

223
00:21:04,520 --> 00:21:06,520
 And civilians too.

224
00:21:06,520 --> 00:21:12,520
 The British developed this lie, and they admitted it as a lie.

225
00:21:12,520 --> 00:21:22,520
 When I interviewed Nigel Nicholson, who was an intelligence officer, who was spreading this deception to the soldiers and to the people.

226
00:21:22,520 --> 00:21:34,520
 If you just get on these trains, cattle cars actually is what they were, just like they used going to Auschwitz, get on them and we will take you to Italy.

227
00:21:34,520 --> 00:21:40,520
 So they, these people voluntarily, they didn't want to go to Yugoslavia.

228
00:21:40,520 --> 00:21:48,520
 They knew they had to surrender to the British somehow, so they got on voluntarily onto these trains, onto the cattle cars.

229
00:21:48,520 --> 00:21:55,520
 And the estimates are, the documents that I found were between 60 and 80 people per car.

230
00:21:55,520 --> 00:21:58,520
 Not even enough room to sit down.

231
00:21:58,520 --> 00:22:03,520
 They would close the door, and then once the door was closed, they would put locks on the outside of the doors.

232
00:22:03,520 --> 00:22:07,520
 And these people thought that they were going to Italy.

233
00:22:07,520 --> 00:22:16,520
 They didn't realize that they were going to Yugoslavia because, again, the British made an agreement with the partisans to stay out of sight.

234
00:22:16,520 --> 00:22:20,520
 Don't let these people know that you're watching them.

235
00:22:20,520 --> 00:22:25,520
 Stay out of the view of these Croatians on the trains.

236
00:22:25,520 --> 00:22:35,520
 The trains would go, and they would go to Rosenbach, on the Rosenbach side of the border, the tunnel.

237
00:22:35,520 --> 00:22:46,520
 And it was only then, when they got to the tunnel, the train stopped, that the partisans took over the train and took control of the train.

238
00:22:46,520 --> 00:22:56,520
 And then the people saw through the slats in the wood from the cattle cars that these red stars on their heads.

239
00:22:56,520 --> 00:23:03,520
 Some of them actually started, according to Nigel Nicholson, British intelligence officer who was there, witnessed it.

240
00:23:03,520 --> 00:23:10,520
 He said that people started even killing themselves inside the cattle cars, rather than be sent back into Yugoslavia.

241
00:23:10,520 --> 00:23:13,520
 Why do you think the British showed such brutality?

242
00:23:13,520 --> 00:23:19,520
 That's a more complicated question than it seems.

243
00:23:19,520 --> 00:23:28,520
 I think that the root of it is a racism on behalf of the British people and a feeling of superiority.

244
00:23:28,520 --> 00:23:30,520
 That's my personal view.

245
00:23:30,520 --> 00:23:40,520
 I asked Dr. Ivo Korski, who lived in Argentina, I went and interviewed him in 1989, I think it was.

246
00:23:40,520 --> 00:23:46,520
 I asked him, are the British racist people?

247
00:23:46,520 --> 00:23:49,520
 And he said an interesting answer.

248
00:23:49,520 --> 00:23:57,520
 He said, the British are not racist, they don't have a racist ideology like the Nazis do, or like the Germans did.

249
00:23:57,520 --> 00:24:01,520
 They have a racist, I'm sorry, they don't have a racist theory.

250
00:24:01,520 --> 00:24:06,520
 They have a racist practice, which is a big difference.

251
00:24:06,520 --> 00:24:14,520
 If you look what the British did in Northern Ireland, what they did in China, what they did in India, in Pakistan, even in Palestine.

252
00:24:14,520 --> 00:24:26,520
 They do seem, and I asked this of a British general, I asked the British general, are the racists, do they have this racist tendency in their souls?

253
00:24:26,520 --> 00:24:33,520
 And he admitted that, I suppose, most British feel superior.

254
00:24:33,520 --> 00:24:39,520
 And for those people that were in Bleiburg, they were just, for them, they were just Slavs.

255
00:24:39,520 --> 00:24:40,520
 That's how they said it.

256
00:24:40,520 --> 00:24:41,520
 Slavs, yes.

257
00:24:41,520 --> 00:24:43,520
 They were just Slavs.

258
00:24:43,520 --> 00:24:52,520
 They didn't realize that the Croatians in Austria were closer to their homeland than the British were to their homeland.

259
00:24:52,520 --> 00:24:59,520
 But for somehow, the mentality of the British was that the Croatians were the foreigners.

260
00:24:59,520 --> 00:25:02,520
 And they used that term too, they were just foreigners.

261
00:25:02,520 --> 00:25:11,520
 In their own, you know, within a few kilometers of their own land, and they were considered foreigners by the British.

262
00:25:11,520 --> 00:25:15,520
 So we can say Bleiburg was ethnic cleansing.

263
00:25:15,520 --> 00:25:25,520
 I think especially Tito used, he didn't ethnically cleanse the Croatian people.

264
00:25:25,520 --> 00:25:28,520
 It wasn't his intention to ethnically cleanse them.

265
00:25:28,520 --> 00:25:38,520
 But he was, he wanted to ethnically cleanse, he wanted to cleanse the concept, the idea of a free Croatia.

266
00:25:38,520 --> 00:25:44,520
 And if he had to kill 700,000 people to do that, he was more than willing to do that.

267
00:25:44,520 --> 00:25:51,520
 And we can also talk about after the war, after 1945, how many people were killed.

268
00:25:51,520 --> 00:26:08,520
 In other ways, through the Secret Service, through Osnot, through their different policies of getting people to come to the office.

269
00:26:08,520 --> 00:26:11,520
 If you want, I can get into this story.

270
00:26:11,520 --> 00:26:16,520
 I, several times I heard this story that somebody was given, this was after '45.

271
00:26:16,520 --> 00:26:19,520
 This is even up to 1950.

272
00:26:19,520 --> 00:26:22,520
 People were given an envelope delivered to their home.

273
00:26:22,520 --> 00:26:25,520
 The envelope was sealed.

274
00:26:25,520 --> 00:26:27,520
 And it says, "Do not open."

275
00:26:27,520 --> 00:26:30,520
 Take this, for example, to Karlovac.

276
00:26:30,520 --> 00:26:34,520
 Take this to, and Boiklovac was there in Karlovac.

277
00:26:34,520 --> 00:26:52,520
 Take this to the, this office, and I believe it was the, I shouldn't, I, I'm losing my line now, but I, I, I believe it was, they were told to deliver it to a specific building.

278
00:26:53,520 --> 00:26:54,520
 They're left with a dilemma.

279
00:26:54,520 --> 00:26:57,520
 Do I open it, to find out what's inside the envelope?

280
00:26:57,520 --> 00:26:59,520
 If I do that, then they'll know I opened it.

281
00:26:59,520 --> 00:27:02,520
 If I don't, I won't know it's inside.

282
00:27:02,520 --> 00:27:07,520
 So many people took the envelope, most people, presented it to Osno office.

283
00:27:07,520 --> 00:27:12,520
 They opened it up, and inside it said, "Kill this person immediately."

284
00:27:12,520 --> 00:27:20,520
 That's where they would take them to places like, um, Javzlovka, for example, by, by truck.

285
00:27:20,520 --> 00:27:21,520
 Of course.

286
00:27:21,520 --> 00:27:26,520
 So, uh, Mr. Palaic, what is, uh, the objective, uh, data?

287
00:27:26,520 --> 00:27:29,520
 How many people were killed in the Blyburg massacre?

288
00:27:29,520 --> 00:27:33,520
 Uh, people talk about the numbers of victims.

289
00:27:33,520 --> 00:27:36,520
 Some reduce that number, uh, some do the opposite.

290
00:27:36,520 --> 00:27:41,520
 Um, my answer to that has always been, I have no idea.

291
00:27:41,520 --> 00:27:49,520
 There's a way to come to a general idea of what that number would be, and that is using demographics.

292
00:27:49,520 --> 00:28:14,520
 I'm not an expert in demographics, but, um, in the, um, and maybe this is a good point to talk about the book that's coming out by my friend, Dr. Ante Chuvalo about Blyburg, where they're using the transcripts from my British interviews with these soldiers and putting into both English and Croatian so that people can read exactly what these British officers said.

293
00:28:15,520 --> 00:28:26,520
 In his, uh, foreword for the book, he talks about, um, a professor who is an expert in demographics, who has done some research on demographics.

294
00:28:26,520 --> 00:28:40,520
 And he has an idea of, um, of how, based on the population before the war, the population after the war, approximately how many people were killed as a result of Blyburg.

295
00:28:40,520 --> 00:28:53,520
 I can only say that you would think that if there were a lot of survivors, that there would be many more survivors who ended up in America, Canada, Australia, uh, Argentina.

296
00:28:53,520 --> 00:29:02,520
 There weren't. There were very few. I had to travel actually to four different continents to find these survivors. There were so few.

297
00:29:02,520 --> 00:29:08,520
 Yes, I understand. But no one was ever charged for those crimes. That's tragedy.

298
00:29:08,520 --> 00:29:13,520
 The closest person that was ever charged, to my understanding, is Bojkavac. Mm-hmm.

299
00:29:13,520 --> 00:29:23,520
 Uh, he was indicted at one point, I think, and then, uh, somehow through technicalities, uh, the case was dismissed.

300
00:29:23,520 --> 00:29:35,520
 But he's the only one that came close to that. So for, you know, you can talk about since 1945 until 1991, people in Croatia were walking.

301
00:29:35,520 --> 00:29:44,520
 And still today, I guess, in places like Vukavari, you're walking down the street with people who were formerly killing you and killing your people.

302
00:29:44,520 --> 00:29:58,520
 In fact, I have a story in the book about one person who was from Karlovat's area, who, uh, I knew somebody that witnessed him killing these Croatians in Jasovka.

303
00:29:58,520 --> 00:30:10,520
 And then, uh, shooting them back in the back of the head that he shot so many people in the back of the head and dumped them into the hole in Jasovka, so many people that the gun would overheat.

304
00:30:10,520 --> 00:30:19,520
 And after the gun overheated, he would take a hammer and smash the back of their head, the skull, and then throw them into the pit.

305
00:30:19,520 --> 00:30:30,520
 And he, that person that did that fled to Canada, where he lived in a place called Mississauga, Canada, just outside of Toronto.

306
00:30:30,520 --> 00:30:36,520
 And he was there among the Croatian people at picnics, lamb roasts, like he was one of them.

307
00:30:36,520 --> 00:30:37,520
 Is he still alive?

308
00:30:37,520 --> 00:30:47,520
 I don't think he's alive now, but his name, the name that was given to me, was Smichiklas, which I guess is a common name for this area.

309
00:30:47,520 --> 00:30:49,520
 Yes, in Karlovat's area, right.

310
00:30:49,520 --> 00:30:51,520
 But, uh, you mentioned Tito.

311
00:30:51,520 --> 00:30:52,520
 You mentioned Tito.

312
00:30:52,520 --> 00:30:54,520
 What responsibility did Tito have?

313
00:30:54,520 --> 00:30:57,520
 And what evidence did you find?

314
00:30:57,520 --> 00:31:10,520
 The, uh, the evidence that I found on Tito, because basically that wasn't my, it wasn't my, um, focus on finding guilt about Tito.

315
00:31:10,520 --> 00:31:16,520
 Well, it seems obvious to me that there was enough, if the partisans, he was in charge of the partisans.

316
00:31:16,520 --> 00:31:17,520
 Of course.

317
00:31:17,520 --> 00:31:19,520
 He was the so-called marshal.

318
00:31:19,520 --> 00:31:25,520
 Uh, I think, um, um, Thompson has another name for him that he uses.

319
00:31:25,520 --> 00:31:33,520
 But if, um, if he was the marshal at the time in charge of all the partisans, then he certainly knew what was going on.

320
00:31:33,520 --> 00:31:36,520
 And if he wanted to stop it, he could have stopped it.

321
00:31:36,520 --> 00:31:50,520
 But I think that, um, the documents that I did find say that he, that he was announcing on the radio that the extermination of these enemies of our people are underway now.

322
00:31:50,520 --> 00:31:52,520
 And they were soon be concluded.

323
00:31:52,520 --> 00:31:55,520
 That was a statement from him.

324
00:31:55,520 --> 00:32:08,520
 Now again, uh, Gerald Draper says that it's, um, he, he and the partisans that took part in the killing were guilty of war crimes, crimes against humanity, crimes against the peace.

325
00:32:08,520 --> 00:32:12,520
 And they could have been charged with war crimes easily.

326
00:32:12,520 --> 00:32:17,520
 This is a former prosecutor at Nuremberg who's saying this, not me.

327
00:32:17,520 --> 00:32:18,520
 Yeah.

328
00:32:18,520 --> 00:32:22,520
 Uh, but what moved you the most in this research?

329
00:32:22,520 --> 00:32:24,520
 Uh, what shocked you?

330
00:32:24,520 --> 00:32:25,520
 About, uh, Blyburn?

331
00:32:25,520 --> 00:32:26,520
 Yes.

332
00:32:26,520 --> 00:32:43,520
 I would have to say how, you know, for example, Tolstoy and I have a different opinion about the guilt of the, the British, uh, military and government in general.

333
00:32:43,520 --> 00:32:44,520
 We have different approaches.

334
00:32:44,520 --> 00:32:53,520
 He's, he's more specific talking about Harold McMillan, for example, or Toby Lowe, who also became Lord, Lord Aldington.

335
00:32:53,520 --> 00:32:55,520
 I don't specify it like that.

336
00:32:55,520 --> 00:33:11,520
 I use the terms that the war crimes prosecutor used, which was no matter what level you are in the government or in the military, if you commit a war crime, it doesn't matter if you've following orders or not.

337
00:33:11,520 --> 00:33:16,520
 The soldier is only responsible to obey lawful orders.

338
00:33:16,520 --> 00:33:20,520
 He's not responsible to obey unlawful orders.

339
00:33:20,520 --> 00:33:27,520
 And if they committed these crimes and they were unlawful orders that they were committed, they're still guilty of war crimes.

340
00:33:27,520 --> 00:33:31,520
 And this doesn't matter if they're a general or if they're a private.

341
00:33:31,520 --> 00:33:38,520
 If they committed these war crimes, they're as guilty as, as the general is.

342
00:33:38,520 --> 00:33:45,520
 So that, um, it was, that was a shock to me that Tolstoy had this opinion.

343
00:33:45,520 --> 00:33:59,520
 The other one was really, you know, the Blyberg, I knew about the deception of the general, um, Clark, for example, in the negotiations.

344
00:33:59,520 --> 00:34:11,520
 And by the way, I do have, uh, an interview with, um, uh, Daniel Serlian, who was one of the two negotiators in the, in the Blyberg castle at the time.

345
00:34:11,520 --> 00:34:27,520
 Um, but really the, this, this very, uh, developed technique or strategy of deception that they used for getting rid of the remaining Croatians, putting them onto trains.

346
00:34:27,520 --> 00:34:31,520
 It's exactly like they did for the, the trains going to Auschwitz.

347
00:34:31,520 --> 00:34:38,520
 And not one British has ever been put on trial for this, never been found guilty, nothing.

348
00:34:38,520 --> 00:34:42,520
 Just, they will, they refuse to even address the issue.

349
00:34:42,520 --> 00:34:44,520
 They just ignore it.

350
00:34:44,520 --> 00:34:46,520
 They didn't even show mercy?

351
00:34:46,520 --> 00:34:49,520
 No, because they received orders.

352
00:34:49,520 --> 00:34:53,520
 They're very similar as the, uh, as the Germans.

353
00:34:53,520 --> 00:34:57,520
 They received an order to do this, and orders were orders.

354
00:34:57,520 --> 00:35:14,520
 And I even have, uh, one of the, the British, uh, officers, uh, Captain, uh, Colin Gunnar, who was there at the bridge in Lavamund, watched the Croatians go over for, uh, one day, one night, one day, he says.

355
00:35:14,520 --> 00:35:16,520
 Thousands of people.

356
00:35:16,520 --> 00:35:19,520
 He says, "I was just following orders."

357
00:35:19,520 --> 00:35:21,520
 That's how he dismissed it.

358
00:35:21,520 --> 00:35:22,520
 Sounds familiar.

359
00:35:22,520 --> 00:35:23,520
 Exactly.

360
00:35:23,520 --> 00:35:27,520
 Uh, did your documentary rock the boat?

361
00:35:27,520 --> 00:35:31,520
 Uh, in, well, I, yes, it did.

362
00:35:31,520 --> 00:35:35,520
 I, I brought it, actually, I smuggled it into Yugoslavia.

363
00:35:35,520 --> 00:35:36,520
 It was still Yugoslavia at the time.

364
00:35:36,520 --> 00:35:37,520
 Yes.

365
00:35:37,520 --> 00:35:39,520
 It was, uh, before 1990, right?

366
00:35:39,520 --> 00:35:43,520
 It was, uh, May of 1991.

367
00:35:43,520 --> 00:35:44,520
 Oh.

368
00:35:44,520 --> 00:35:46,520
 It was even before the referendum, I believe.

369
00:35:46,520 --> 00:35:47,520
 Mm-hmm.

370
00:35:47,520 --> 00:35:51,520
 Uh, so, again, you know, I think, uh, Auntie Belia was here at the time working.

371
00:35:51,520 --> 00:35:53,520
 He had moved from Canada.

372
00:35:53,520 --> 00:35:57,520
 And he arranged for me to show it in the Mimare Museum.

373
00:35:57,520 --> 00:35:58,520
 In Sagret.

374
00:35:58,520 --> 00:35:59,520
 Uh, in May of 1991.

375
00:35:59,520 --> 00:36:00,520
 Good.

376
00:36:00,520 --> 00:36:01,520
 Uh, in May of 1991.

377
00:36:01,520 --> 00:36:04,520
 So, it was a small salon that they have off to the left of the entrance.

378
00:36:04,520 --> 00:36:07,520
 It held maybe 50, 75 people.

379
00:36:07,520 --> 00:36:09,520
 But it was full.

380
00:36:09,520 --> 00:36:15,520
 But, but at certain points in the movie, when we talk about the kill, the partisans killing,

381
00:36:15,520 --> 00:36:21,520
 the slaughters, there would be screaming from behind, "Laji! Laji!"

382
00:36:21,520 --> 00:36:22,520
 Uh-huh.

383
00:36:22,520 --> 00:36:28,520
 Of people that had infiltrated into the group, but they wanted to somehow cause a little problem,

384
00:36:28,520 --> 00:36:30,520
 uh, which they never did, really.

385
00:36:30,520 --> 00:36:33,520
 All they could, well, yellow in the back was "Laji!"

386
00:36:33,520 --> 00:36:34,520
 "Laji!"

387
00:36:34,520 --> 00:36:35,520
 Da.

388
00:36:35,520 --> 00:36:36,520
 Ne bih rekla da su bile "Laji!"

389
00:36:36,520 --> 00:36:37,520
 Okay.

390
00:36:37,520 --> 00:36:39,520
 Uh, well, uh, one question.

391
00:36:39,520 --> 00:36:43,520
 Today, uh, communist symbols are being glorified in Croatia.

392
00:36:43,520 --> 00:36:45,520
 Uh, not much, but, okay.

393
00:36:45,520 --> 00:36:46,520
 What do you think about it?

394
00:36:46,520 --> 00:36:47,520
 Okay.

395
00:36:47,520 --> 00:36:59,520
 As somebody who grew up anti-communist, as somebody who came here during the war from 1991

396
00:36:59,520 --> 00:37:10,520
 to '95, who was being shot at by people who were carrying that flag, wearing that red star,

397
00:37:10,520 --> 00:37:16,520
 and calling the Croatian soldiers who were fighting for independence ustase,

398
00:37:16,520 --> 00:37:24,520
 I find it difficult to believe that it is even tolerated in this country,

399
00:37:24,520 --> 00:37:33,520
 that people still have the audacity to proudly display the Yugoslav flag,

400
00:37:33,520 --> 00:37:39,520
 who were probably just, just to talk about here, uh, Tito being a hero,

401
00:37:39,520 --> 00:37:44,520
 or putting red stars on the top of buildings in Rijeka.

402
00:37:44,520 --> 00:37:50,520
 I just can't believe, and the attacks made on singers who are patriotic,

403
00:37:50,520 --> 00:37:56,520
 people like Thompson, who are patriotic Croatian people, and they are attacked because they're,

404
00:37:56,520 --> 00:38:02,520
 I can't believe that they hate their own people so much that they would attack them like that.

405
00:38:02,520 --> 00:38:09,520
 And after all of the centuries of fighting for freedom and independence, for their sovereignty,

406
00:38:09,520 --> 00:38:10,520
 and now…

407
00:38:10,520 --> 00:38:11,520
 And so many deaths?

408
00:38:11,520 --> 00:38:13,520
 It just, it bothers me.

409
00:38:13,520 --> 00:38:18,520
 And what do you think about greeting Zadomspremni?

410
00:38:18,520 --> 00:38:26,520
 I think Zadomspremni, the historical term, I heard it many times during the war,

411
00:38:26,520 --> 00:38:30,520
 of '91 to '95, I heard it many times.

412
00:38:30,520 --> 00:38:38,520
 Nobody ever condemned those people for yelling that when they were being protected by those people.

413
00:38:38,520 --> 00:38:40,520
 They would go to the front.

414
00:38:40,520 --> 00:38:47,520
 And I mean, I used to, I spent a lot of time in Zagreb, and I spent a lot of time in Dobreslav Parga's office,

415
00:38:47,520 --> 00:38:51,520
 um, at the Starčević Dome by the Glavnikolet war.

416
00:38:51,520 --> 00:38:57,520
 And I, you know, I was there with those guys, and, um, many times when they were going to the front,

417
00:38:57,520 --> 00:38:59,520
 they would yell Zadomspremni.

418
00:38:59,520 --> 00:39:06,520
 Now, one person complained about that when they were defending them during a war in which,

419
00:39:06,520 --> 00:39:12,520
 if Croatians would have lost, they knew that they would have been killed.

420
00:39:12,520 --> 00:39:20,520
 Just like they were in Slavonia, and Borovoselo, and, and, and Vukova, and other places.

421
00:39:20,520 --> 00:39:25,520
 So, it's a distraction in, in one sense.

422
00:39:25,520 --> 00:39:30,520
 And in the other sense, I don't understand how they can be so offended by that word.

423
00:39:30,520 --> 00:39:38,520
 And yet, those same people who are offended by a phrase are so quick to put up a Yugoslav flag,

424
00:39:38,520 --> 00:39:48,520
 or to talk about how great the partisans were, or how easy they can say smut fascizma,

425
00:39:48,520 --> 00:39:50,520
 how easy they are to say that.

426
00:39:50,520 --> 00:39:52,520
 And we're all, we're all against fascism.

427
00:39:52,520 --> 00:39:58,520
 I think that there's, I've never met any person living today that is for fascism.

428
00:39:58,520 --> 00:40:01,520
 They're for sovereignty, they're for independence.

429
00:40:01,520 --> 00:40:05,520
 But somehow they've construed that to mean fascism.

430
00:40:05,520 --> 00:40:12,520
 And they're still yelling this slogan that they used during the war, and after the war.

431
00:40:12,520 --> 00:40:14,520
 Well, up until the end of Yugoslavia.

432
00:40:14,520 --> 00:40:15,520
 Of course.

433
00:40:15,520 --> 00:40:18,520
 You mentioned Hoss and Mr. Dobroslav Paraga.

434
00:40:18,520 --> 00:40:27,520
 Can you share your story about Hoss in your life and about Mr. Paraga with us, please?

435
00:40:27,520 --> 00:40:41,520
 Well, I first met Paraga in Canada. This was just shortly after he got out of prison, a political prison, and I think he was in…

436
00:40:41,520 --> 00:40:42,520
 Goliotok.

437
00:40:42,520 --> 00:40:43,520
 Goliotok.

438
00:40:43,520 --> 00:40:44,520
 Goliotok.

439
00:40:44,520 --> 00:40:46,520
 Not Goliotok, I think he was in…

440
00:40:46,520 --> 00:40:47,520
 Never mind.

441
00:40:47,520 --> 00:40:48,520
 Yeah, never mind.

442
00:40:48,520 --> 00:41:02,520
 But he was with Tudjman, and the rest of them were in this political prison.

443
00:41:02,520 --> 00:41:09,520
 So once he got released, everybody was wondering, where is Paraga, where is Paraga?

444
00:41:09,520 --> 00:41:19,520
 Well, I just happened to be in Toronto, Canada at the time, me and some other guys, that by this time I had already been kind of recruited into this independence movement.

445
00:41:19,520 --> 00:41:32,520
 Of people who had been fighting for years before I ever was, and maybe we can talk about that if you'd like.

446
00:41:32,520 --> 00:41:40,520
 So I met him for the first time there. There were some Slovenian journalists there talking to him, so that's the first time that we met.

447
00:41:40,520 --> 00:41:41,520
 It was in Canada, right?

448
00:41:41,520 --> 00:41:42,520
 In Canada, yeah.

449
00:41:42,520 --> 00:41:55,520
 And then in May of 1991, when I showed the film for the first time in Mimara, I somehow got in contact with him again.

450
00:41:55,520 --> 00:42:01,520
 And I went to his home and I showed him the film at his house with his family and everything.

451
00:42:01,520 --> 00:42:14,520
 And so that was in May of 1991. And then I came back in October of 1991, after things had really blown up, literally, I guess.

452
00:42:14,520 --> 00:42:23,520
 And by that time he was already in the, he had already taken over the building at Starchevich Dome.

453
00:42:23,520 --> 00:42:32,520
 And so I went in there and talked to him. And after that I routinely went in there to, just to have conversations with him and talk to him.

454
00:42:32,520 --> 00:42:47,520
 His, his, his group wasn't the first one that I wanted to join. I came here in October 1991 with four other guys.

455
00:42:47,520 --> 00:43:07,520
 Two guys were from Sen, Marko Stipaničić, Robert Ciacic, Pero Ivčec from Jasr Basko and then a really good friend of mine, Ante Pranec from Banja Luka.

456
00:43:07,520 --> 00:43:09,520
 So we came here to fight, actually.

457
00:43:09,520 --> 00:43:10,520
 Okay.

458
00:43:10,520 --> 00:43:11,520
 And so we came...

459
00:43:11,520 --> 00:43:14,520
 In October, you said, in October 1991.

460
00:43:14,520 --> 00:43:15,520
 Yeah.

461
00:43:15,520 --> 00:43:23,520
 So when we got here, we had also been in contact with these guys that went into Yazovka.

462
00:43:23,520 --> 00:43:28,520
 I don't know if you, you had the guest a couple of times here to Yurcevic.

463
00:43:28,520 --> 00:43:29,520
 Professor Yosip Yurcevic.

464
00:43:29,520 --> 00:43:34,520
 He was involved in discovering Yazovka along with two other guys.

465
00:43:34,520 --> 00:43:39,520
 And so I knew these guys again from Canada.

466
00:43:39,520 --> 00:43:40,520
 We got in touch with them.

467
00:43:40,520 --> 00:43:46,520
 And it just happened to be that one of the guys, Davar Bukovic, we call him Zhu.

468
00:43:46,520 --> 00:43:47,520
 Zhu.

469
00:43:47,520 --> 00:43:48,520
 Zhu.

470
00:43:48,520 --> 00:43:49,520
 Okay.

471
00:43:49,520 --> 00:43:51,520
 Because he has this red hair.

472
00:43:51,520 --> 00:43:55,520
 And we got in touch with him.

473
00:43:55,520 --> 00:44:00,520
 And he just happened to be friends with the bodyguard for Tomislav Mirchip.

474
00:44:00,520 --> 00:44:06,520
 So, Mirchip at the time was in the hospital recovering from getting shot.

475
00:44:06,520 --> 00:44:17,520
 I think he was, I forget exactly where he was when he was shot, but anyway, he was recovering from the wounds in the hospital.

476
00:44:17,520 --> 00:44:23,520
 And this friend of ours was the bodyguard who was sitting outside the door of the hospital room.

477
00:44:23,520 --> 00:44:30,520
 And so he made an arrangement for us to go in, the five of us to go in and talk to him about joining his group.

478
00:44:30,520 --> 00:44:32,520
 So we did.

479
00:44:32,520 --> 00:44:34,520
 And we talked to him for quite a while.

480
00:44:34,520 --> 00:44:36,520
 And, you know, we got accepted.

481
00:44:36,520 --> 00:44:44,520
 And he said, you know, come up to where we're at.

482
00:44:44,520 --> 00:44:48,520
 And this guy will bring you here.

483
00:44:48,520 --> 00:44:50,520
 So the next day, we're all ready to go.

484
00:44:50,520 --> 00:44:51,520
 We're all packed.

485
00:44:51,520 --> 00:44:54,520
 We're ready to be picked up.

486
00:44:54,520 --> 00:45:05,520
 And it turns out the guy who was the bodyguard was charged with killing a guy outside the train station.

487
00:45:05,520 --> 00:45:08,520
 They got Glavnikonivor in Zagreb.

488
00:45:08,520 --> 00:45:11,520
 And who he said was working for Kos.

489
00:45:11,520 --> 00:45:13,520
 So we waited and waited.

490
00:45:13,520 --> 00:45:15,520
 He was, he wasn't coming out of jail.

491
00:45:15,520 --> 00:45:21,520
 He was, we eventually, my friends got tired of waiting.

492
00:45:21,520 --> 00:45:24,520
 They ended up going, two of them went to Seine.

493
00:45:24,520 --> 00:45:26,520
 And one of them joined Hos.

494
00:45:26,520 --> 00:45:30,520
 And he also was very good friends with Paraga.

495
00:45:30,520 --> 00:45:32,520
 So he joined Hos.

496
00:45:32,520 --> 00:45:39,520
 And I was kind of left just, I was waiting to go with Medichip still.

497
00:45:39,520 --> 00:45:40,520
 Okay.

498
00:45:40,520 --> 00:45:43,520
 You wanted to be a part of Hos.

499
00:45:43,520 --> 00:45:44,520
 But.

500
00:45:44,520 --> 00:45:51,520
 Well, Hos was my, after a while, after some period of time went by and I got tired of waiting to get picked up by Medichip.

501
00:45:51,520 --> 00:45:55,520
 Because of the guy who was in jail.

502
00:45:55,520 --> 00:45:57,520
 I then went to Hos.

503
00:45:57,520 --> 00:45:59,520
 And I was, I had it arranged.

504
00:45:59,520 --> 00:46:00,520
 Okay.

505
00:46:00,520 --> 00:46:05,520
 Again, strange things happen.

506
00:46:05,520 --> 00:46:12,520
 The day that I was going to report there at Starchvich Dome to go in.

507
00:46:12,520 --> 00:46:13,520
 I had my backpack.

508
00:46:13,520 --> 00:46:14,520
 I went there with my bag.

509
00:46:14,520 --> 00:46:20,520
 It was the exact same day that Paraga got picked up by the special police.

510
00:46:20,520 --> 00:46:25,520
 And he was, he himself was sitting in jail at that time.

511
00:46:25,520 --> 00:46:37,520
 So I couldn't, these guys I was supposed to go with, they couldn't take me in unless he officially gave his stamp saying that I was permitted to go.

512
00:46:37,520 --> 00:46:39,520
 So that fell through.

513
00:46:39,520 --> 00:46:43,520
 Although I worked with Hos pretty closely.

514
00:46:43,520 --> 00:46:47,520
 What is your relationship with Hos like today?

515
00:46:47,520 --> 00:46:52,520
 Oh, with, to me, they were always good fighters.

516
00:46:52,520 --> 00:46:57,520
 They were always, they're patriots.

517
00:46:57,520 --> 00:47:06,520
 Domolubi, they were willing to die for their country, for their families, for their villages, for their towns.

518
00:47:06,520 --> 00:47:10,520
 I don't know how anybody can say anything negatively about them.

519
00:47:10,520 --> 00:47:24,520
 And especially, especially if you're a head of government and you hate the flag that says Hos so much that you turn your back on it and walk away.

520
00:47:24,520 --> 00:47:26,520
 I don't understand.

521
00:47:26,520 --> 00:47:33,520
 They probably protected you during the war, unless you were somewhere else during the war, in Geneva or something.

522
00:47:33,520 --> 00:47:37,520
 Then maybe you didn't feel like they were protecting you, but…

523
00:47:37,520 --> 00:47:40,520
 Yes, a little bit hard to understand.

524
00:47:40,520 --> 00:47:45,520
 But during the homeland war, you were a journalist, right?

525
00:47:45,520 --> 00:47:46,520
 Freelancer.

526
00:47:46,520 --> 00:47:47,520
 Journalist.

527
00:47:47,520 --> 00:47:48,520
 Journalist.

528
00:47:48,520 --> 00:47:49,520
 Okay.

529
00:47:49,520 --> 00:47:57,520
 You worked for the Croatian Ministry of Information from October 1991 to 1993, but you were also a foreign agent, right?

530
00:47:57,520 --> 00:47:59,520
 For the Ministry of Defense, yeah.

531
00:47:59,520 --> 00:48:00,520
 Yeah.

532
00:48:00,520 --> 00:48:01,520
 And I worked…

533
00:48:01,520 --> 00:48:03,520
 I'm all ears.

534
00:48:03,520 --> 00:48:13,520
 We worked directly for, me and three other guys who formed this group, worked directly for Gojko Shushak.

535
00:48:13,520 --> 00:48:19,520
 So we didn't report to anybody except for him, which is kind of a nice position to be in.

536
00:48:19,520 --> 00:48:30,520
 So that gave us permission to act on behalf of the Croatian military defense anywhere, including the United States.

537
00:48:30,520 --> 00:48:36,520
 Because in the United States, you have to register as a foreign agent in order to represent a foreign government.

538
00:48:36,520 --> 00:48:38,520
 So we were doing that.

539
00:48:38,520 --> 00:48:53,520
 That gave us permission to act in business for the Croatian government, searching out for different various items that might be used in Croatia during a war.

540
00:48:53,520 --> 00:49:06,520
 Anything, really, from, you know, guns to uniforms, for example, or helmets or bulletproof vests or anything.

541
00:49:06,520 --> 00:49:21,520
 But it also gave us authorization to act in information or propaganda, let's say, for lack of a better term, for the Croatian government in the United States.

542
00:49:21,520 --> 00:49:34,520
 So, as a result of that, I guess, '93, even though a lot of…

543
00:49:34,520 --> 00:49:49,520
 I was… eventually I was indicted in 1996 for transferring military equipment to Croatia during the war without a permit,

544
00:49:49,520 --> 00:49:54,520
 without authorization and violation of the arms embargo against Yugoslavia at the time.

545
00:49:54,520 --> 00:49:59,520
 So, you were accused of arms smuggling, right, in the USA?

546
00:49:59,520 --> 00:50:00,520
 Yes.

547
00:50:00,520 --> 00:50:01,520
 1996.

548
00:50:01,520 --> 00:50:02,520
 1996.

549
00:50:02,520 --> 00:50:03,520
 1996.

550
00:50:03,520 --> 00:50:04,520
 They finally charged me.

551
00:50:04,520 --> 00:50:05,520
 Yes.

552
00:50:05,520 --> 00:50:07,520
 But they had been following me.

553
00:50:07,520 --> 00:50:10,520
 And, for example, in 1992, they raided my home.

554
00:50:10,520 --> 00:50:21,520
 The federal agents, the American federal agents, raided my home, looking for documents, money, weapons, anything that I might have in my home.

555
00:50:21,520 --> 00:50:24,520
 So, they raided… they had quite a few people.

556
00:50:24,520 --> 00:50:28,520
 Six o'clock in the morning, they came in and searched my house.

557
00:50:28,520 --> 00:50:29,520
 What was your sin?

558
00:50:29,520 --> 00:50:47,520
 My sin was, I guess, because I had been arrested in Germany for smuggling… they say smuggling weapons into… into European Union in violation of some law.

559
00:50:47,520 --> 00:50:48,520
 That's what they said.

560
00:50:48,520 --> 00:50:54,520
 That's what initiated the whole process that allowed them to come to my house and search the house.

561
00:50:54,520 --> 00:50:59,520
 And where did those weapons end up?

562
00:50:59,520 --> 00:51:11,520
 Well, the weapons that they caught me with in Germany, there's other things that ended up coming through the borders.

563
00:51:11,520 --> 00:51:14,520
 I can even talk about that if you'd like.

564
00:51:14,520 --> 00:51:27,520
 And we can talk a little about Antun Kikash and how he kind of messed things up a little bit for us when they had to close the Zagreb airport, because we were bringing a lot of things in through the airport.

565
00:51:27,520 --> 00:51:37,520
 And after he came with an airplane full of these things, they shut the airport and they ruined everything.

566
00:51:37,520 --> 00:51:42,520
 So, that prevented us from doing a lot of this stuff.

567
00:51:42,520 --> 00:51:50,520
 But the reason I was caught in Germany is because the airport was closed and I was coming here with my own personal weapon to fight.

568
00:51:50,520 --> 00:51:55,520
 The weapons weren't for… I didn't smuggle those weapons for smuggling purposes.

569
00:51:55,520 --> 00:52:00,520
 I brought them in to use myself, including some night vision equipment.

570
00:52:00,520 --> 00:52:03,520
 But it was for personal use.

571
00:52:03,520 --> 00:52:10,520
 So, when I was arrested in Germany, that started everything going.

572
00:52:10,520 --> 00:52:13,520
 They started following me more and more.

573
00:52:13,520 --> 00:52:14,520
 They were…

574
00:52:14,520 --> 00:52:23,520
 And they ended up for five years going through my garbage all the time, looking for documents, looking for any scraps of evidence that they could use against me.

575
00:52:23,520 --> 00:52:42,520
 Tapping my telephones, following me, using the phone numbers that I had registered on my phone, who I called, and then following that in this maze of who they talked to.

576
00:52:42,520 --> 00:52:45,520
 And so, it just led to a lot of investigation.

577
00:52:45,520 --> 00:52:47,520
 That went on for five years.

578
00:52:47,520 --> 00:52:55,520
 And finally, there was a thing called the statute of limitations, which for that particular offense was five years.

579
00:52:55,520 --> 00:52:56,520
 And they…

580
00:52:56,520 --> 00:53:06,520
 I had 12 days left or 13 days left before the statute of limitations ran out.

581
00:53:06,520 --> 00:53:09,520
 After that point, they couldn't indict me.

582
00:53:09,520 --> 00:53:12,520
 So, 12 days before, they indicted me.

583
00:53:12,520 --> 00:53:25,520
 And then I looked at another two and a half years of going to trial, court proceedings, motions to dismiss, motions to have evidence destroyed.

584
00:53:25,520 --> 00:53:28,520
 Then if I can talk about a little bit of…

585
00:53:28,520 --> 00:53:29,520
 Please do.

586
00:53:29,520 --> 00:53:42,520
 In that two and a half year period, the prosecutor in America came to me and they said, "Look, you're looking at 10 years per charge.

587
00:53:42,520 --> 00:53:43,520
 You have six charges.

588
00:53:43,520 --> 00:53:48,520
 You're looking at possible 60 years in prison if they do a consecutive."

589
00:53:48,520 --> 00:53:51,520
 And I felt that they would have done it consecutive, not concurrent.

590
00:53:51,520 --> 00:54:00,520
 So, they had a choice between doing 10 years, just rolling all those six charges into one charge for 10 years.

591
00:54:00,520 --> 00:54:03,520
 Or, if they really wanted to, they could make it 60 years.

592
00:54:03,520 --> 00:54:15,520
 And I believe that they wanted to do 60 years because long before the war in Croatia ever started, I was involved in other things with the Croatian independence movement.

593
00:54:15,520 --> 00:54:18,520
 They were still after me for those things.

594
00:54:18,520 --> 00:54:29,520
 So, if they couldn't get me for those things that they thought I was involved in, they could get me on this.

595
00:54:29,520 --> 00:54:31,520
 So, I was confident that they were going to give me 60 years.

596
00:54:31,520 --> 00:54:44,520
 So, they came to me and they said, "We will give you 14 months in prison, guarantee 14 months in prison, but you have to tell us everything you did, who was involved, individuals who were involved,

597
00:54:44,520 --> 00:54:49,520
 how you did it, what you did, who supplied the money, everything."

598
00:54:49,520 --> 00:54:51,520
 And I said, "I'm not going to do it.

599
00:54:51,520 --> 00:54:56,520
 I'll take my chances with 60 years in prison."

600
00:54:56,520 --> 00:55:02,520
 Because a lot of these were friends of mine, friends that I considered brothers.

601
00:55:02,520 --> 00:55:04,520
 My kids still call them uncle.

602
00:55:04,520 --> 00:55:06,520
 Their kids call me uncle.

603
00:55:06,520 --> 00:55:13,520
 It was a very close relationship that we had and I wasn't going to then.

604
00:55:13,520 --> 00:55:20,520
 One of the people that I protected by not talking was a multi-millionaire who is still living today.

605
00:55:20,520 --> 00:55:25,520
 I think he never, maybe until today, he doesn't know I protected him from himself.

606
00:55:25,520 --> 00:55:27,520
 Is he a Croat or?

607
00:55:27,520 --> 00:55:28,520
 He's a Croatian, yeah.

608
00:55:28,520 --> 00:55:29,520
 Okay, Croatian.

609
00:55:29,520 --> 00:55:34,520
 And have you ever thought, is Croatia worth it?

610
00:55:34,520 --> 00:55:40,520
 It is worth it.

611
00:55:40,520 --> 00:55:47,520
 I think it could be going in a better direction now than it has been going.

612
00:55:47,520 --> 00:56:02,520
 So, I think it's a shame, the sovereignty, the amount of sovereignty and independence that it has already given up just in 30 years.

613
00:56:02,520 --> 00:56:07,520
 And I don't know how much more they're willing to give up even further.

614
00:56:07,520 --> 00:56:18,520
 But, you know, if you're looking at shortly after the war of independence that you fought for for centuries,

615
00:56:18,520 --> 00:56:25,520
 and you're so willing now to give your currency away,

616
00:56:25,520 --> 00:56:30,520
 you're willing to give a certain amount of your sovereignty away to join the European Union,

617
00:56:30,520 --> 00:56:35,520
 to have some other leaders in Geneva dictating what you should do.

618
00:56:35,520 --> 00:56:43,520
 Just like in previous centuries you had Austria-Hungarians, you had the Hungarians, you had the Turks,

619
00:56:43,520 --> 00:56:48,520
 you had the Nazis, you had the Italians, and now you're going to voluntarily...

620
00:56:48,520 --> 00:56:53,520
 I couldn't understand how after all this fighting for centuries,

621
00:56:53,520 --> 00:56:58,520
 you're so willing to just give up something so precious as sovereignty.

622
00:56:58,520 --> 00:57:02,520
 So, is it worth fighting for? It is.

623
00:57:02,520 --> 00:57:11,520
 I'm an old man now, so, you know, it's up to the younger generation to do something.

624
00:57:11,520 --> 00:57:13,520
 To do what?

625
00:57:13,520 --> 00:57:17,520
 That's the question, right?

626
00:57:17,520 --> 00:57:20,520
 How about starting with the vote?

627
00:57:20,520 --> 00:57:21,520
 Yes.

628
00:57:21,520 --> 00:57:26,520
 You know, I love the way the young people have responded to Thompson.

629
00:57:26,520 --> 00:57:31,520
 I love the fact that they're willing to walk for miles to go to a concert.

630
00:57:31,520 --> 00:57:38,520
 That they're yelling all of his songs, no matter how young they are at a festival or at a concert, they know his songs.

631
00:57:38,520 --> 00:57:39,520
 I think that's fantastic.

632
00:57:39,520 --> 00:57:48,520
 But if you're willing to do all that, go stand in line and vote.

633
00:57:48,520 --> 00:57:55,520
 And vote for the people who are going to support your vision of Croatia.

634
00:57:55,520 --> 00:58:01,520
 Not somebody else's vision, not the least of two evils or three evils.

635
00:58:01,520 --> 00:58:07,520
 Vote according to what your heart is telling you for the sovereignty of your country.

636
00:58:07,520 --> 00:58:12,520
 So, that would be what I would hope that they would start, just vote for the right people.

637
00:58:12,520 --> 00:58:16,520
 Mr. Palaic, just to clarify your indictment.

638
00:58:16,520 --> 00:58:25,520
 The federal prosecutor dropped the charges against you and after that the federal judge agreed and dismissed all charges.

639
00:58:25,520 --> 00:58:27,520
 Who was responsible for that?

640
00:58:27,520 --> 00:58:29,520
 Who was responsible for that?

641
00:58:29,520 --> 00:58:31,520
 I'm glad you brought me back to that question.

642
00:58:31,520 --> 00:58:40,520
 Because I really, every year my wife and I, we go to Miragoi and we visit the grave of Goiko Shushak.

643
00:58:40,520 --> 00:58:48,520
 Who was responsible really for saving me from 60 years in prison.

644
00:58:48,520 --> 00:58:53,520
 I totally give him credit for that.

645
00:58:53,520 --> 00:58:58,520
 If you want, I can tell you the story about how that came about.

646
00:58:58,520 --> 00:59:00,520
 It's kind of an unbelievable story.

647
00:59:00,520 --> 00:59:07,520
 But he was friends with William Perry, who was the Minister of Defense for America.

648
00:59:07,520 --> 00:59:10,520
 Kind of friends, working friends, let's say.

649
00:59:10,520 --> 00:59:13,520
 But I think Perry had a lot of respect for Shushak.

650
00:59:13,520 --> 00:59:27,520
 So, I had been working behind the scenes with various people that I knew in the Croatian government still.

651
00:59:27,520 --> 00:59:36,520
 Some of them working with the intelligence agencies in Croatia, trying to get them to do something.

652
00:59:36,520 --> 00:59:46,520
 And what I really were hoping that they could do is at least, when the Germans arrested me in Germany with these weapons, they confiscated them.

653
00:59:46,520 --> 00:59:55,520
 And they had them in some kind of a vault waiting to send back to America where they would use them for my trial.

654
00:59:55,520 --> 01:00:02,520
 One of the first things I wanted to happen was for those weapons to disappear.

655
01:00:02,520 --> 01:00:09,520
 I didn't want that evidence to go back to America because without the evidence, it would be a much more difficult trial.

656
01:00:09,520 --> 01:00:17,520
 Especially because the weapons that they confiscated me with were even illegal in the United States.

657
01:00:17,520 --> 01:00:29,520
 They were machine guns, basically, that I had converted from a single-fire semi-automatic to a full auto-automatic, which was illegal in the United States.

658
01:00:29,520 --> 01:00:32,520
 So, I wanted that destroyed.

659
01:00:32,520 --> 01:00:34,520
 So, that was the first thing.

660
01:00:34,520 --> 01:00:43,520
 And the second thing, if they could do anything to work behind the scenes with the American government to get the case dismissed.

661
01:00:43,520 --> 01:00:47,520
 And then, at some point, things got very quiet.

662
01:00:47,520 --> 01:00:50,520
 My communications dropped off with Croatia.

663
01:00:50,520 --> 01:00:52,520
 Nobody was responding to me anymore.

664
01:00:52,520 --> 01:00:56,520
 Because you were in trouble, of course.

665
01:00:56,520 --> 01:00:59,520
 Well, that's what I thought.

666
01:00:59,520 --> 01:01:01,520
 I thought it was because I was in trouble.

667
01:01:01,520 --> 01:01:04,520
 What I didn't know is they were already working behind the scenes.

668
01:01:04,520 --> 01:01:06,520
 And they will never admit to that.

669
01:01:06,520 --> 01:01:10,520
 I think the American government and the Croatian government will never admit to that.

670
01:01:10,520 --> 01:01:28,520
 I was only told this, for one thing, I have documents from Germany that says that the German intelligence requested those weapons so that they could use them in some kind of a demonstration.

671
01:01:28,520 --> 01:01:31,520
 During that period, they got lost.

672
01:01:31,520 --> 01:01:33,520
 According to the German intelligence.

673
01:01:33,520 --> 01:01:34,520
 Lost.

674
01:01:34,520 --> 01:01:35,520
 Lost.

675
01:01:35,520 --> 01:01:36,520
 That's right.

676
01:01:36,520 --> 01:01:37,520
 So, that was that.

677
01:01:37,520 --> 01:01:39,520
 Those got lost.

678
01:01:39,520 --> 01:01:45,520
 And then, I thought things had just disappeared.

679
01:01:45,520 --> 01:01:52,520
 What I didn't know is that they were working behind the scenes to actually get the case dismissed.

680
01:01:52,520 --> 01:01:55,520
 And Goyker Shushak was very big in that.

681
01:01:55,520 --> 01:02:06,520
 Because I know the person, I don't want to say too much because he just recently, he was working for the Croatian government at the time.

682
01:02:06,520 --> 01:02:19,520
 He was involved with going to Shushak and telling him the whole story of how the weapons happened to be confiscated or what the story was.

683
01:02:19,520 --> 01:02:29,520
 And, and I believe, I'm just trying to be careful with names now because…

684
01:02:29,520 --> 01:02:30,520
 Take your time.

685
01:02:30,520 --> 01:02:35,520
 There's still some people who are still around that were involved in that.

686
01:02:35,520 --> 01:02:36,520
 I understand you completely.

687
01:02:36,520 --> 01:02:40,520
 But they're high in leadership, let's put it that way.

688
01:02:40,520 --> 01:02:43,520
 In addition to Goyker Shushak.

689
01:02:43,520 --> 01:02:49,520
 And so, Shushak had a conversation with William Peary.

690
01:02:49,520 --> 01:02:57,520
 And then shortly after that, and I forgot exactly when it was, I think it was October of 1996.

691
01:02:57,520 --> 01:03:03,520
 The case, I get a phone call from my lawyer and they say, "I don't know what happened.

692
01:03:03,520 --> 01:03:09,520
 But your case is being dismissed by the prosecutor, federal prosecutor."

693
01:03:09,520 --> 01:03:12,520
 I sensed what was happening, but I didn't know for sure.

694
01:03:12,520 --> 01:03:14,520
 I still didn't know for sure.

695
01:03:14,520 --> 01:03:16,520
 It wasn't until I came to Croatia.

696
01:03:16,520 --> 01:03:25,520
 During a couple of years, that period of time when I was being investigated or when I was indicted, two and a half years, I couldn't travel to Croatia.

697
01:03:25,520 --> 01:03:35,520
 As soon as I got my passport back and I was allowed to come to Croatia, I came and I talked to this individual who was working for the government, who was responsible for talking to Shushak.

698
01:03:35,520 --> 01:03:36,520
 He told me the whole story.

699
01:03:36,520 --> 01:03:53,520
 In fact, part of the story was that he told me that he himself, and he worked for one of the intelligence agencies, and he himself was being followed by another office intelligence agency.

700
01:03:53,520 --> 01:03:57,520
 I think it was Sis at the time, was following him.

701
01:03:57,520 --> 01:04:01,520
 And he asked the guy, "Why are you following me around for?

702
01:04:01,520 --> 01:04:03,520
 You know, I know you're following me.

703
01:04:03,520 --> 01:04:04,520
 Why are you following me?"

704
01:04:04,520 --> 01:04:09,520
 And they said, "It's not about you, but it's about Michael Palaic.

705
01:04:09,520 --> 01:04:13,520
 We want to find out what the connection is."

706
01:04:13,520 --> 01:04:23,520
 And so they were following him, hoping to get a connection of me, and trying to understand what my connection was with this guy that was working with intelligence.

707
01:04:23,520 --> 01:04:29,520
 So we can say, you became the enemy of Croatia.

708
01:04:29,520 --> 01:04:32,520
 In what sense?

709
01:04:32,520 --> 01:04:39,520
 In a sense that intelligence like Sis?

710
01:04:39,520 --> 01:04:40,520
 Oh, no, I'm sorry.

711
01:04:40,520 --> 01:04:41,520
 No.

712
01:04:41,520 --> 01:04:42,520
 I gave you the wrong idea.

713
01:04:42,520 --> 01:04:43,520
 Okay.

714
01:04:43,520 --> 01:04:44,520
 It wasn't that.

715
01:04:44,520 --> 01:04:49,520
 The CIA asked Sis to find out what the connection was.

716
01:04:49,520 --> 01:05:01,520
 So maybe people don't know, and maybe I shouldn't even be talking, but the CIA actually was training Croatian intelligence at the time of independence.

717
01:05:01,520 --> 01:05:18,520
 They were here on the ground, and we actually, we, Croatian government ended up kicking one of these CIA guys out of the country, persona non grata, because of other things he was involved in that the Croatian government didn't like.

718
01:05:18,520 --> 01:05:35,520
 He was a Croatian guy, by the way, born in Croatia, was in the Vietnam War during the Vietnam War, ended up with special forces, and then they made him a military attaché, Americans made him a military attaché in Zagreb.

719
01:05:35,520 --> 01:05:42,520
 And he was doing some nefarious things that he shouldn't have been doing, and he got kicked out.

720
01:05:42,520 --> 01:05:45,520
 Well, he was one of the CIA trainers for the Croatian intelligence.

721
01:05:45,520 --> 01:05:46,520
 What a story.

722
01:05:46,520 --> 01:05:53,520
 So anyway, there was a close relationship between Croatian intelligence and CIA.

723
01:05:53,520 --> 01:05:54,520
 Those two intelligence.

724
01:05:54,520 --> 01:05:57,520
 So the CIA asked somebody from Sis to do it.

725
01:05:57,520 --> 01:05:59,520
 It wasn't because I was an enemy of Sis.

726
01:05:59,520 --> 01:06:04,520
 It was that CIA wanted to find more information out about me.

727
01:06:04,520 --> 01:06:08,520
 Tell me more about you.

728
01:06:08,520 --> 01:06:09,520
 You.

729
01:06:09,520 --> 01:06:10,520
 Right.

730
01:06:10,520 --> 01:06:12,520
 But just one second.

731
01:06:12,520 --> 01:06:18,520
 I would like to go back to your Croatian roots and to your granny.

732
01:06:18,520 --> 01:06:19,520
 Ljubica.

733
01:06:19,520 --> 01:06:22,520
 You wrote this book za Hrvatsku moje bake.

734
01:06:22,520 --> 01:06:26,520
 Sjedećanstvo o rođenju države.

735
01:06:26,520 --> 01:06:28,520
 Evo sad ću, samo ću na hrvatskom reći.

736
01:06:28,520 --> 01:06:30,520
 Dakle, sjajna stvar.

737
01:06:30,520 --> 01:06:32,520
 Knjiga je izdana na hrvatskom jeziku.

738
01:06:32,520 --> 01:06:37,520
 i sjedočanstvo jednog hrvata, kako kaže knjiga.

739
01:06:37,520 --> 01:06:44,520
 Američko hrvata treće generacije koji se priključio pokretu za slobodu Hrvatske u dobi od 22 godine.

740
01:06:44,520 --> 01:06:45,520
 E sad.

741
01:06:45,520 --> 01:06:47,520
 So, my question.

742
01:06:47,520 --> 01:06:49,520
 Why did you write this book?

743
01:06:49,520 --> 01:07:18,520
 First, one reason I wrote, there are many reasons, but one of the reasons I wrote it is because, you know, after you get a certain age, I'll be 72 shortly, I'm 71 now, and you start thinking you would like people to know maybe what happened in the past, especially my children, and know a little bit about what I did, what happened, why I did what I, why I was away from home so much, why I was away from home so much.

744
01:07:18,520 --> 01:07:22,520
 Why I put myself under this pressure of the government.

745
01:07:22,520 --> 01:07:25,520
 So, that's one reason.

746
01:07:25,520 --> 01:07:39,520
 The other reason I would like the people in Croatia, the reason I had it translated into Croatia was because I would like people here to know that independence here didn't just start in 1991.

747
01:07:39,520 --> 01:07:50,520
 It started decades before that, and there was a lot of people that carried this flag of independence, this Bariak.

748
01:07:50,520 --> 01:07:51,520
 Bariak.

749
01:07:51,520 --> 01:07:52,520
 Into the future.

750
01:07:52,520 --> 01:07:53,520
 Hrvatski Bariak.

751
01:07:53,520 --> 01:07:54,520
 That's right.

752
01:07:54,520 --> 01:07:55,520
 Hrvatski Bariak.

